In 2013 a major supreme court case, the United States v. Windsor, resulted in the Supreme Court striking down part of a law that banned federal recognition of same-sex marriages. Soon after this, another Supreme Court ruling (Obergefell v. Hodges) legalized same-sex marriage across the nation. These rulings mean that married same-sex couples are now entitled to the same rights enjoyed by heterosexual married couples. These rights include Social Security benefits, hospital visitation rights, healthcare benefits, and military family benefits. However, despite these advances, LGBT people still have no federal law to protect them from discrimination in housing or employment.

An Aging Population

While the life expectancy of an American born in 1900 was less than 50 years, an American born in 2011 can expect to live to age 80. By 2050, the median age of the population will live longer, and exert more political influence. These factors have strained the country's social welfare system, especially Social Security and Medicare. In 2010, the federal government spent less than $100 billion on social welfare. By 2013, the amount had increased to $1.9 trillion.

With the large baby-boom generation reaching retirement age, the issue of older care has become critical. Failing birthrates over the past two decades have meant that when the huge population of baby boomers retires, there will not be enough workers to cover their Social Security benefits. Politicians have been debating this impending reality.

In his second term, President Bush called for privatizing Social Security by allowing younger workers to invest some of their earnings in individual retirement accounts. Critics defeated the measure, saying that it would put younger workers at the mercy of fluctuating stock market returns without addressing the shortfall of funds. Today the debate continues.

Energy and the Environment

On June 25, 2013, President Obama addressed an audience at Georgetown University on the subject of the environment. Briefly mentioning that the twelve warmest years in recorded history had occurred over the course of the previous fifteen years, he focused on the problems of global warming.

Last year, temperatures in some areas of the ocean reached record highs, and ice in the Arctic shrank to its smallest size on record—faster than most models had predicted it would. These are facts.

— President Obama, Georgetown University, June 25, 2013

President Obama's Climate Action Plan

EPA REGULATORY GOALS

  • Speed up the process of implementing regulations on greenhouse gas emissions
  • Issue flexible regulations to individual states to help reduce emissions
  • Replace use of hydrofluorocarbons (HFCs) in the United States with alternatives
  • Promote scientific research and development
  • Work with foreign, state, and local governments to solve issues
  • Improve the EPA's internal management and workforce
  • Empower communities to advance the cause of environmental protection
  • Support the Presidential Council for an Advanced Energy Economy

SOURCE: Presidential Climate Action Project

Coastal areas of the United States will be under threat if, as many scientists predict, the warming of the atmosphere leads to a rise in sea levels. Rising sea levels are already leading to periodic flooding, especially in cities and towns. With Florida likely experiencing an increase in sea levels due to the sea area, a concerning threat to the levels, which have been rising for the last 100 years, will accelerate, threatening cities further inland.

But global warming has implications far beyond rising seas. The Environmental Protection Agency reports that in Alaska, where the increase in warming temperatures is most acute, the landscape is thawing, while permafrost forest wildfires are increasing, while sea ice is decreasing. Lakes are draining on the ice, and together, this melting permafrost, which may lead to ground subsidence, is a direct threat to transportation networks and buildings.

Legislating to Protect the Environment

In recent years, environmental issues have created political controversy. Some deny that our planet is experiencing a period of global warming or even warming temperatures. Some deny that such warming is the product of human activity. Those who do believe that humans are the cause of global warming have urged the federal government to pass legislation. But given the variety of opinion on environmental matters, it is surprising that government regulations have attracted plenty of opposition. The main argument against environmental legislation is that it hurts the economy and the nation's industries.

In the 1970s and 1980s, regulations were passed to control emissions from power plants, prompting many coal industry officials to attack the administration for waging a "war on coal." Many Republicans also criticized Obama's efforts to support renewable energy. When Donald Trump became president, he attempted to undo much of Obama's environmental efforts, signing an executive order limiting the government's enforcement of climate regulations. Trump claimed that this would help protect American jobs.

The Environment and Local Economies

Environmental issues have become controversial largely because the environment is closely tied to local economies. The continental United States can be divided into four main environmental regions: the West, the South, the Northeast, and the Midwest. In the West, water is an important environmental and economic issue because it is so scarce. Population growth and development put pressure on this important resource, which must be shared by private homes and businesses. Recent periods of drought in California, which supplies produce to the nation, have had a dramatic effect on the state's farming economy.

The West is a region with vast tracts of land owned by the federal government. The government's management of this land for logging, grazing and other development. In recent years the opening up of oil and gas development on public land has become a controversial issue. Other issues there differ from environmental issues elsewhere. The 2010 Deepwater Horizon spill in the Gulf of Mexico created major environmental problems along the coast of many Southern states. In the Midwest, the Keystone XL pipeline project attracted opposition and litigation to stop it. This pipeline, which would transport crude oil from Canada to the oil refineries in Oklahoma and Texas, has been approved by President Trump. Critics have condemned this project for its possible damage to the environment, while the project's supporters promise that it will bring jobs and a reliable oil supply.
